WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:03.250 --> 00:00:04.130
- Good afternoon.

00:00:04.130 --> 00:00:06.070
My name is Immaculata
De Vivo, and I

00:00:06.070 --> 00:00:09.430
am the Interim Co-director for
Science Programming this year

00:00:09.430 --> 00:00:11.260
for the life sciences.

00:00:11.260 --> 00:00:14.170
And I am delighted
and privileged to be

00:00:14.170 --> 00:00:16.750
introducing our speakers today.

00:00:16.750 --> 00:00:20.950
The lecture is entitled
"Science Sounds Strange,"

00:00:20.950 --> 00:00:23.950
and it's actually the first
lecture in the Undiscovered

00:00:23.950 --> 00:00:26.050
Science Series.

00:00:26.050 --> 00:00:31.270
The Undiscovered Series,
or the actual conference,

00:00:31.270 --> 00:00:33.520
will be held on October 26.

00:00:33.520 --> 00:00:37.540
And the conference itself
showcases the critical role

00:00:37.540 --> 00:00:41.760
of unexpected or unforeseeable
discovery in science.

00:00:41.760 --> 00:00:47.570
And my co-partner, Lisa Goodman,
this was her brainchild.

00:00:47.570 --> 00:00:50.830
The goal of that day is to
gather not only scientists

00:00:50.830 --> 00:00:52.810
but educators, students,
and journalists,

00:00:52.810 --> 00:00:55.210
media producers,
and others to start

00:00:55.210 --> 00:00:58.390
a new, very public conversation
about how scientists

00:00:58.390 --> 00:01:01.090
should make discoveries.

00:01:01.090 --> 00:01:04.000
Today, I am privileged
to present Professor John

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:07.360
Huth, who is a Donner
Professor of Science

00:01:07.360 --> 00:01:10.240
in the Department of Physics
here at Harvard University.

00:01:10.240 --> 00:01:13.840
He served as the faculty
co-director of science

00:01:13.840 --> 00:01:16.540
at this Institute, at
Radcliffe, and he works mainly

00:01:16.540 --> 00:01:19.960
in the field of experimental
particle physics.

00:01:19.960 --> 00:01:25.330
I also would like to introduce
our thereminist, Dorit

00:01:25.330 --> 00:01:27.450
Chrysler, who's sitting
in the front row.

00:01:27.450 --> 00:01:29.680
She's an Austrian-born
thereminist.

00:01:29.680 --> 00:01:32.530
She's a composer,
producer, and singer.

00:01:32.530 --> 00:01:36.850
And her focus is to promote the
theremin in contemporary music.

00:01:36.850 --> 00:01:39.550
I actually did a
little research myself

00:01:39.550 --> 00:01:41.620
so that I wouldn't
sound too foolish today.

00:01:41.620 --> 00:01:43.509
And I found out
that this instrument

00:01:43.509 --> 00:01:45.550
is one of the only
instruments that can be played

00:01:45.550 --> 00:01:47.180
without actually touching it.

00:01:47.180 --> 00:01:49.270
So yes.

00:01:49.270 --> 00:01:52.060
She's also the founder of
the New York Theremin Society

00:01:52.060 --> 00:01:53.830
and started America's
first school

00:01:53.830 --> 00:01:56.920
for theremin,
KidCoolThereminSchool.

00:01:56.920 --> 00:01:59.710
She has performed with the San
Francisco Symphony Orchestra

00:01:59.710 --> 00:02:02.410
and is featured on the
soundtrack of the HBO

00:02:02.410 --> 00:02:04.890
documentary, Going Clear.

00:02:04.890 --> 00:02:08.770
She's been commissioned for
MoMA in the Venice Biennial,

00:02:08.770 --> 00:02:14.480
and she's performed at Lincoln
Center, Vienna, Coachella--

00:02:14.480 --> 00:02:18.970
just a whole variety
of different venues.

00:02:18.970 --> 00:02:23.090
And I guess,
without further ado,

00:02:23.090 --> 00:02:27.820
I'd like to present Professor
John Huth to the podium.

00:02:27.820 --> 00:02:28.766
Thank you.

00:02:28.766 --> 00:02:32.550
[APPLAUSE]

00:02:34.900 --> 00:02:35.400
- OK.

00:02:35.400 --> 00:02:36.420
Well, welcome.

00:02:36.420 --> 00:02:39.990
Actually, Dorit is the
main speaker and performer

00:02:39.990 --> 00:02:41.730
on the theremin.

00:02:41.730 --> 00:02:44.100
So the way we're going
to do it is Dorit's going

00:02:44.100 --> 00:02:47.680
to come up, explain the
theremin a little bit,

00:02:47.680 --> 00:02:52.170
perform some pieces, and also
talk about the amazing and odd

00:02:52.170 --> 00:02:54.810
life of Leo Theremin.

00:02:54.810 --> 00:02:57.120
And at some moment,
she'll ask me to come up,

00:02:57.120 --> 00:03:00.060
and I'll give you some of the
physical principles underlying

00:03:00.060 --> 00:03:04.110
the performance of the theremin
and some of the espionage work

00:03:04.110 --> 00:03:06.760
that Theremin was engaged in.

00:03:06.760 --> 00:03:07.944
So Dorit.

00:03:07.944 --> 00:03:11.840
[APPLAUSE]

00:03:17.210 --> 00:03:18.110
- Thank you, John.

00:03:18.110 --> 00:03:21.230
Thank you for having me.

00:03:21.230 --> 00:03:25.640
Some years ago, I was invited
at a friend's house in New York.

00:03:25.640 --> 00:03:29.390
And he pointed me
towards a very unassuming

00:03:29.390 --> 00:03:38.660
looking object consisting of
a wooden box with a metal rod.

00:03:38.660 --> 00:03:40.350
Some power was plugged in.

00:03:40.350 --> 00:03:44.960
And then suddenly, I heard
a really unusual and strange

00:03:44.960 --> 00:03:50.090
sound that seemed to
correlate with the slightest

00:03:50.090 --> 00:03:52.760
motion of my body.

00:03:52.760 --> 00:03:59.540
And I was instantly smitten
and surprised that I had never

00:03:59.540 --> 00:04:02.930
heard about this
device that turned out

00:04:02.930 --> 00:04:05.210
to be a music instrument.

00:04:05.210 --> 00:04:09.210
And I wanted to find
out, how does it work?

00:04:09.210 --> 00:04:11.270
How can it be played?

00:04:11.270 --> 00:04:16.380
And why is this instrument
not more popular?

00:04:16.380 --> 00:04:20.300
So this was my first
encounter with the theremin.

00:04:20.300 --> 00:04:22.370
And I would like
to know who of you

00:04:22.370 --> 00:04:25.790
here has ever played
a theremin before?

00:04:25.790 --> 00:04:27.680
OK.

00:04:27.680 --> 00:04:33.140
We have a few arms-- about
10, which is not bad.

00:04:33.140 --> 00:04:36.310
But it should be more.

00:04:36.310 --> 00:04:37.780
[LAUGHTER]

00:04:37.780 --> 00:04:40.890
- [INAUDIBLE]

00:04:40.890 --> 00:04:41.520
- OK.

00:04:41.520 --> 00:04:42.300
Yeah.

00:04:42.300 --> 00:04:47.495
The theremin really came
to life by accident.

00:04:50.250 --> 00:04:52.610
It was invented-- created--

00:04:52.610 --> 00:04:57.320
by a Russian physicist,
Lev Theremin.

00:04:57.320 --> 00:05:01.070
He was working at the time
at the Physical Technical

00:05:01.070 --> 00:05:03.440
Institute in St. Petersburg.

00:05:03.440 --> 00:05:06.380
And he was working
on the principle

00:05:06.380 --> 00:05:10.340
of one of the first
motion detector systems.

00:05:10.340 --> 00:05:13.760
And he actually
created an alarm system

00:05:13.760 --> 00:05:17.480
that was installed
at the Moscow Bank,

00:05:17.480 --> 00:05:20.480
and it's based on a principle
that, then, John later

00:05:20.480 --> 00:05:25.430
will more elaborately
explain to all of us.

00:05:25.430 --> 00:05:30.730
All I can do is demonstrate this
alarm system that he created--

00:05:30.730 --> 00:05:33.680
just basically created
the electromagnetic field

00:05:33.680 --> 00:05:34.570
and the body.

00:05:37.265 --> 00:05:41.260
[ELECTRONIC WHIRRING NOISE]

00:05:41.260 --> 00:05:43.750
Approaching a certain
distance, the body

00:05:43.750 --> 00:05:47.005
is a conductor
changing the frequency

00:05:47.005 --> 00:05:51.640
and creating a sound
in the audible range.

00:05:51.640 --> 00:05:53.860
When he worked on this
in the laboratory,

00:05:53.860 --> 00:05:56.560
strange noises emerged.

00:05:56.560 --> 00:06:00.370
And because Lev Theremin
also was a cellist,

00:06:00.370 --> 00:06:04.570
he had the idea to turn
this principle into a music

00:06:04.570 --> 00:06:08.385
instrument, hence the theremin.

00:06:11.120 --> 00:06:13.970
The theremin, of course,
is a completely different

00:06:13.970 --> 00:06:17.750
musical interface than all
the traditional instruments.

00:06:17.750 --> 00:06:19.850
And that, and for
many other reasons,

00:06:19.850 --> 00:06:23.600
it really had problems
establishing itself.

00:06:23.600 --> 00:06:27.350
It's also extremely hard
to play because it responds

00:06:27.350 --> 00:06:29.750
to the slightest
motion of the body,

00:06:29.750 --> 00:06:32.960
even when you think
you're not moving.

00:06:32.960 --> 00:06:34.940
You still are
constantly in motion,

00:06:34.940 --> 00:06:36.500
and it changes the pitch.

00:06:36.500 --> 00:06:41.930
When you play theremin, you
really dive into micro-space.

00:06:41.930 --> 00:06:46.400
Because of this invention-- it
was the era of electrification

00:06:46.400 --> 00:06:48.350
in the Soviet Union.

00:06:48.350 --> 00:06:52.670
It was 1919, meaning the
theremin is turning 100

00:06:52.670 --> 00:06:53.960
next year.

00:06:53.960 --> 00:06:58.450
And he became a prodigy of
Lenin with this instrument.

00:06:58.450 --> 00:07:00.410
There's a nice photo
where Lenin himself

00:07:00.410 --> 00:07:02.210
is playing the theremin.

00:07:02.210 --> 00:07:05.540
And he was sent across
Europe to promote

00:07:05.540 --> 00:07:10.040
the technical
achievements of Russia.

00:07:10.040 --> 00:07:13.130
And he made it all
the way to New York.

00:07:13.130 --> 00:07:17.400
And there, he had
his first review--

00:07:17.400 --> 00:07:20.960
1927-- by The New York Times.

00:07:20.960 --> 00:07:26.450
There was a headline that
said "Ether Wave Music Amazes

00:07:26.450 --> 00:07:27.740
Savants."

00:07:27.740 --> 00:07:31.150
And it featured an
interview by Lev Theremin

00:07:31.150 --> 00:07:33.230
where he quotes verbatim--

00:07:33.230 --> 00:07:37.220
very humbly-- he
says, "My apparatus

00:07:37.220 --> 00:07:43.190
will liberate the
composer of the despotism

00:07:43.190 --> 00:07:47.240
of the well-tempered
12-tone piano scale.

00:07:47.240 --> 00:07:52.910
It offers infinite tonal
possibility and literally

00:07:52.910 --> 00:07:56.710
thousands of tone colors."

00:07:56.710 --> 00:08:01.280
To give you now a possibility
to make your own impression,

00:08:01.280 --> 00:08:05.480
I will perform one of the
pieces that Lev performed

00:08:05.480 --> 00:08:08.390
that time, one of the
pieces of his repertoire,

00:08:08.390 --> 00:08:09.665
so you can hear for yourself.

00:08:23.483 --> 00:08:27.475
[MUSIC - CAMILLE SAINT SAENS,
 "THE SWAN"]

00:11:42.584 --> 00:11:46.576
[APPLAUSE]

00:11:51.860 --> 00:11:54.320
As you can see, one really
has to concentrate and hold

00:11:54.320 --> 00:11:55.520
the body very still.

00:11:55.520 --> 00:11:59.270
And just two days ago, when
we did something like this,

00:11:59.270 --> 00:12:02.120
I was criticized because people
want to know, how do you really

00:12:02.120 --> 00:12:02.620
play this?

00:12:02.620 --> 00:12:06.770
So I'm just going to give
a very fast explanation.

00:12:06.770 --> 00:12:10.140
So you might have noticed
this is the pitch antenna.

00:12:10.140 --> 00:12:12.730
So the closer my hand goes
to the pitch antenna--

00:12:12.730 --> 00:12:14.590
[ELECTRONIC NOTE PLAYING]

00:12:14.590 --> 00:12:16.270
--the higher the note.

00:12:16.270 --> 00:12:19.090
And this is the volume antenna.

00:12:19.090 --> 00:12:23.230
So the further away, the louder.

00:12:23.230 --> 00:12:26.470
And when I have my hand just
above the antenna, it's quiet.

00:12:26.470 --> 00:12:30.430
So it's an interplay
of the horizontal

00:12:30.430 --> 00:12:32.650
and the vertical fields.

00:12:32.650 --> 00:12:38.800
And each note is sculpted in
the air by the volume and tenor

00:12:38.800 --> 00:12:43.120
while I'm constantly
intonating and balancing,

00:12:43.120 --> 00:12:45.940
as if I'm buzzing
around the flower.

00:12:45.940 --> 00:12:46.790
That's the pitch.

00:12:46.790 --> 00:12:48.400
And my hand is a
bumblebee, and I'm

00:12:48.400 --> 00:12:53.170
trying to land on that
flower to get the pitch.

00:12:53.170 --> 00:12:55.867
That's the basic
approach on the theremin.

00:12:55.867 --> 00:12:57.450
I just want to talk
a little bit more.

00:12:57.450 --> 00:13:00.130
So Lev Theremin
came to New York,

00:13:00.130 --> 00:13:03.860
and he made quite a splash
with this new device.

00:13:03.860 --> 00:13:06.310
And even though the
theremin, at that time,

00:13:06.310 --> 00:13:09.130
was only applied to
classical music, which

00:13:09.130 --> 00:13:14.050
really limited its
tonal abilities,

00:13:14.050 --> 00:13:16.340
people still were very excited.

00:13:16.340 --> 00:13:20.230
And he found some sponsors
and started his laboratory

00:13:20.230 --> 00:13:21.880
in Manhattan.

00:13:21.880 --> 00:13:25.660
And he also had the
great luck to find

00:13:25.660 --> 00:13:30.520
a tremendously talented theremin
virtuoso, Clara Rockmore.

00:13:30.520 --> 00:13:33.130
She was a violinist
who injured her hand

00:13:33.130 --> 00:13:35.440
and couldn't play
the violin anymore.

00:13:35.440 --> 00:13:39.670
And she became a
proficient thereminist that

00:13:39.670 --> 00:13:42.580
really set the bar
very high of what

00:13:42.580 --> 00:13:44.830
is possible on this instrument.

00:13:44.830 --> 00:13:50.350
She then did a lot of tours
with Paul Robeson, activist

00:13:50.350 --> 00:13:51.440
and baritone.

00:13:51.440 --> 00:13:54.030
And if I could go
back in time, I

00:13:54.030 --> 00:13:58.280
would really probably choose
being at one of their concerts

00:13:58.280 --> 00:13:58.780
back then.

00:13:58.780 --> 00:14:02.830
I think that would have been
really, really exciting.

00:14:02.830 --> 00:14:07.510
Theremin sold his patent
for the theremin to RCA.

00:14:07.510 --> 00:14:13.450
So that made the theremin the
very first electric instrument

00:14:13.450 --> 00:14:16.540
that was actually
mass manufactured.

00:14:16.540 --> 00:14:21.460
So it was really the
birth of electronic music.

00:14:21.460 --> 00:14:26.740
The only problem was that
RCA marketed the theremin not

00:14:26.740 --> 00:14:32.020
really in a very successful
and realistic way.

00:14:32.020 --> 00:14:35.500
The theremin was certainly
a luxury item, price-wise.

00:14:35.500 --> 00:14:41.680
And they promoted it as a
friendly house instrument,

00:14:41.680 --> 00:14:48.850
easy to play for
the whole family,

00:14:48.850 --> 00:14:53.350
in the same note
like the home organs.

00:14:53.350 --> 00:14:58.720
And obviously, that proved
to be fatally wrong.

00:14:58.720 --> 00:15:01.380
In addition, there
was the Black Friday.

00:15:01.380 --> 00:15:04.160
The economic crashed.

00:15:04.160 --> 00:15:06.350
So that didn't help
things, either.

00:15:06.350 --> 00:15:11.620
And Theremin found himself
suddenly in tremendous debt.

00:15:11.620 --> 00:15:15.110
And he had himself
established in New York.

00:15:15.110 --> 00:15:18.040
He had married
one of the members

00:15:18.040 --> 00:15:21.620
of the first African-American
ballet troops.

00:15:21.620 --> 00:15:24.370
And suddenly, he was gone.

00:15:24.370 --> 00:15:26.330
And there are many rumors.

00:15:26.330 --> 00:15:28.900
There's one book
and one documentary,

00:15:28.900 --> 00:15:31.690
and there are different
accounts of claiming

00:15:31.690 --> 00:15:36.460
that he had been a spy
all along for Russia

00:15:36.460 --> 00:15:38.710
and chose to go back.

00:15:38.710 --> 00:15:42.940
And others say he was
kidnapped by the KGB.

00:15:42.940 --> 00:15:45.460
We don't know what happened.

00:15:45.460 --> 00:15:47.200
His wife in the
States didn't know.

00:15:47.200 --> 00:15:49.340
He was just suddenly gone.

00:15:49.340 --> 00:15:52.870
And we do know that--

00:15:52.870 --> 00:15:55.710
Stalin was in
power at that time.

00:15:55.710 --> 00:15:59.500
And he was first sent to
Siberia and then ended

00:15:59.500 --> 00:16:03.820
in one of those
notorious science camps.

00:16:03.820 --> 00:16:07.000
His whole family didn't
think he was alive anymore.

00:16:07.000 --> 00:16:12.710
And he worked on technical
devices benefiting the state.

00:16:12.710 --> 00:16:17.590
And interesting enough,
he applied the principle

00:16:17.590 --> 00:16:24.430
of this instrument also for
another new electronic device,

00:16:24.430 --> 00:16:25.925
namely the bug--

00:16:25.925 --> 00:16:26.425
"The Thing."

00:16:29.120 --> 00:16:36.150
A seal was given by children
to the American Ambassador,

00:16:36.150 --> 00:16:39.220
and he hung it right
behind his desk.

00:16:39.220 --> 00:16:43.120
And thanks to Theremin's
listening device

00:16:43.120 --> 00:16:46.620
that didn't exist until then,
the Russians could listen

00:16:46.620 --> 00:16:51.100
into all conversations for
many years until the British

00:16:51.100 --> 00:16:52.360
detected a signal.

00:16:52.360 --> 00:16:53.950
And there's a very
nice photo when

00:16:53.950 --> 00:16:56.440
the UN declared the Cold War.

00:16:56.440 --> 00:16:59.590
They're actually holding up
this very seal that contained

00:16:59.590 --> 00:17:01.750
the bug that Lev Theremin made.

00:17:01.750 --> 00:17:03.910
And so maybe at
this point, I would

00:17:03.910 --> 00:17:07.000
like to ask the esteemed
John Huth onstage

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:11.868
to explain the technical
details of all these.

00:17:11.868 --> 00:17:12.368
- Thank you.

00:17:12.368 --> 00:17:15.812
[APPLAUSE]

00:17:17.300 --> 00:17:20.940
So Dorit will come up
and talk some more.

00:17:20.940 --> 00:17:24.530
But I'll try to explain as
best I can some of the science

00:17:24.530 --> 00:17:27.980
between both the
theremin and the bug.

00:17:27.980 --> 00:17:32.510
So most people probably
know that like charges

00:17:32.510 --> 00:17:35.785
repel in electromagnetism,
and unlike charges attract.

00:17:35.785 --> 00:17:38.030
So a plus-minus charge
will attract each other.

00:17:38.030 --> 00:17:40.790
A plus charge and a plus
charge will repel each other.

00:17:40.790 --> 00:17:44.310
And a minus charge and a minus
charge will repel each other.

00:17:44.310 --> 00:17:49.070
So in our bodies, our bodies
are, to some approximation,

00:17:49.070 --> 00:17:49.820
saline.

00:17:49.820 --> 00:17:51.450
That means it's salt water.

00:17:51.450 --> 00:17:52.880
And that means
charges can freely

00:17:52.880 --> 00:17:55.350
flow throughout our bodies.

00:17:55.350 --> 00:17:58.190
So if I take a charge
and put it on, let's say,

00:17:58.190 --> 00:18:00.680
the pitch antenna-- say I put
a bunch of positive charges

00:18:00.680 --> 00:18:02.420
on the pitch antenna--

00:18:02.420 --> 00:18:04.310
the negative charges
in my body are

00:18:04.310 --> 00:18:07.160
going to be attracted
toward the pitch antenna.

00:18:07.160 --> 00:18:09.970
And the positive charges
are going to get repelled.

00:18:09.970 --> 00:18:12.620
Because the positive charge
here repels the positive charges

00:18:12.620 --> 00:18:15.770
in my body and attracts
the negative charges.

00:18:15.770 --> 00:18:20.600
And what that does is it creates
a kind of natural device,

00:18:20.600 --> 00:18:23.180
if you like, called a capacitor.

00:18:23.180 --> 00:18:26.600
A capacitor is simply a
device that holds charge.

00:18:26.600 --> 00:18:29.480
This was done by,
among other people,

00:18:29.480 --> 00:18:32.030
Ben Franklin, who created
this in a Leyden jar, who

00:18:32.030 --> 00:18:36.620
was able to store the charge
from the base of a thundercloud

00:18:36.620 --> 00:18:39.320
with a kite to try to figure
out whether there were

00:18:39.320 --> 00:18:42.590
positive or negative charges at
the base of the thundercloud.

00:18:42.590 --> 00:18:47.300
So the circuit
that's used to get

00:18:47.300 --> 00:18:51.890
both the pitch and the volume
involves the following process.

00:18:51.890 --> 00:18:54.540
There's another device
inside here called

00:18:54.540 --> 00:18:56.390
an inductor, which
sometimes looks

00:18:56.390 --> 00:18:59.170
like a little spring wound up.

00:18:59.170 --> 00:19:04.130
And that has a property similar
to holding electric charge.

00:19:04.130 --> 00:19:07.020
It holds magnetic
fields in some way.

00:19:07.020 --> 00:19:10.560
And depending on the
distance your hand is

00:19:10.560 --> 00:19:16.610
to either the pitch antenna
or the volume antenna,

00:19:16.610 --> 00:19:19.230
you're going to get a different
amount of capacitance.

00:19:19.230 --> 00:19:21.380
Now, the way the
circuit works is,

00:19:21.380 --> 00:19:23.750
depending on the value
of the capacitance,

00:19:23.750 --> 00:19:26.690
there is a natural
frequency that emerges.

00:19:26.690 --> 00:19:29.240
And that natural
frequency is the basis

00:19:29.240 --> 00:19:33.960
for how you change the
pitch or the volume.

00:19:33.960 --> 00:19:35.640
Now, let me explain
this a little bit.

00:19:35.640 --> 00:19:39.290
There is almost identical
math in a situation which

00:19:39.290 --> 00:19:41.270
is probably more
familiar to you,

00:19:41.270 --> 00:19:43.290
which is a child's swing set.

00:19:43.290 --> 00:19:45.650
And in the child's
swing set, depending

00:19:45.650 --> 00:19:47.900
on the length of the
rope for the swing,

00:19:47.900 --> 00:19:51.170
you're going to get a different
frequency that the swing moves

00:19:51.170 --> 00:19:52.110
back and forth.

00:19:52.110 --> 00:19:57.320
So the longer the rope,
the slower the swing moves.

00:19:57.320 --> 00:20:00.740
So the capacitance basically
plays the same role

00:20:00.740 --> 00:20:08.000
as the length of the rope
that holds up the swing--

00:20:08.000 --> 00:20:11.330
the length of the rope
that holds up the swing.

00:20:11.330 --> 00:20:14.240
So that is the main
controlling factor.

00:20:14.240 --> 00:20:16.280
So you'll have a
natural frequency

00:20:16.280 --> 00:20:18.080
that then gets interrogated.

00:20:18.080 --> 00:20:23.420
Now, the big issue is that the
natural frequency associated

00:20:23.420 --> 00:20:26.390
with either the pitch or
the volume that comes out

00:20:26.390 --> 00:20:28.970
is going to be, typically,
at a radio frequency.

00:20:28.970 --> 00:20:31.410
So it's somewhere of
the order of megahertz,

00:20:31.410 --> 00:20:34.460
which is well beyond the
range of human hearing.

00:20:34.460 --> 00:20:38.000
And the real game is to,
then, take that signal

00:20:38.000 --> 00:20:40.084
and convert it into
an audio signal

00:20:40.084 --> 00:20:41.750
around the range of
human hearing, which

00:20:41.750 --> 00:20:47.340
is 30 hertz to about 20,000
hertz cycles per second.

00:20:47.340 --> 00:20:49.610
And to do that, what
Theremin did was he

00:20:49.610 --> 00:20:53.670
took a fairly recent
invention, for him,

00:20:53.670 --> 00:20:55.220
which was called heterodyning.

00:20:55.220 --> 00:20:57.140
And in heterodyning,
what you do is

00:20:57.140 --> 00:21:01.460
you introduce a frequency that's
close to the natural frequency

00:21:01.460 --> 00:21:03.890
that occurs between the
capacitance of the hand

00:21:03.890 --> 00:21:07.352
and the antenna and
the inductor inside.

00:21:07.352 --> 00:21:08.810
And then, what that
does is there's

00:21:08.810 --> 00:21:12.740
an interference between the
frequency source that you have

00:21:12.740 --> 00:21:15.740
inside here and the frequency
that you're naturally creating

00:21:15.740 --> 00:21:17.760
by having your hand near here.

00:21:17.760 --> 00:21:19.310
And the interference
between the two

00:21:19.310 --> 00:21:22.850
will then create a much
lower frequency pattern.

00:21:22.850 --> 00:21:25.040
And then, you take that
lower frequency pattern

00:21:25.040 --> 00:21:26.690
and turn that into
the sound that

00:21:26.690 --> 00:21:32.450
emerges both in controlling the
volume here and the pitch here.

00:21:32.450 --> 00:21:34.550
And that's what comes out.

00:21:34.550 --> 00:21:38.780
Heterodyning is also
used in FM radio.

00:21:38.780 --> 00:21:40.880
Frequency modulation
is probably the term

00:21:40.880 --> 00:21:43.630
that you're more familiar
with, whereas the word

00:21:43.630 --> 00:21:46.700
heterodyning is kind of
just out in left field.

00:21:46.700 --> 00:21:49.880
So more or less,
that's how this works.

00:21:49.880 --> 00:21:54.650
Now, the other thing
is how the bug works.

00:21:54.650 --> 00:21:57.500
And the bug is kind of
an inverse of the way

00:21:57.500 --> 00:21:58.870
the theremin operates.

00:21:58.870 --> 00:22:00.180
So let me explain a little bit.

00:22:00.180 --> 00:22:01.180
So what you want to do--

00:22:01.180 --> 00:22:03.330
I mean, how would you
think about how to do this?

00:22:03.330 --> 00:22:05.840
You know, Stalin handed
Theremin this problem,

00:22:05.840 --> 00:22:08.090
and he has this bag
of electrical tricks

00:22:08.090 --> 00:22:08.820
up his sleeve.

00:22:08.820 --> 00:22:11.000
And so you want to
take this plaque that

00:22:11.000 --> 00:22:14.210
was given to Averell
Harriman in 1949,

00:22:14.210 --> 00:22:16.950
and you want to be able to
listen in on the conversation.

00:22:16.950 --> 00:22:19.700
So you have, again, sound
from the human voice,

00:22:19.700 --> 00:22:23.630
which is roughly 30
hertz to 20,000 hertz.

00:22:23.630 --> 00:22:27.859
But then, you want to convert it
into a radio frequency signal.

00:22:27.859 --> 00:22:29.900
OK, so it's the inverse
of what's happening here,

00:22:29.900 --> 00:22:32.108
is you're taking something
which is a radio frequency

00:22:32.108 --> 00:22:34.430
signal electrically,
turning it into a sound.

00:22:34.430 --> 00:22:36.350
So you just invert the problem.

00:22:36.350 --> 00:22:41.750
So what Lev did was he
created a kind of circuit,

00:22:41.750 --> 00:22:43.040
again, with a capacitor.

00:22:43.040 --> 00:22:46.640
And the capacitor, in
this case, one side of it

00:22:46.640 --> 00:22:49.670
could vibrate back
and forth associated

00:22:49.670 --> 00:22:50.660
with the voice pattern.

00:22:50.660 --> 00:22:53.840
So somebody would speak, the
air molecules would vibrate,

00:22:53.840 --> 00:22:56.900
and then part of this capacitor
would vibrate back and forth.

00:22:56.900 --> 00:22:59.780
The distance between a fixed
plate and this vibrating plate

00:22:59.780 --> 00:23:01.340
would change the capacitance.

00:23:01.340 --> 00:23:04.610
And it would, again, be part of
the circuit, which is actually

00:23:04.610 --> 00:23:05.480
a passive circuit.

00:23:05.480 --> 00:23:06.920
There were no
batteries involved.

00:23:06.920 --> 00:23:10.340
Because who's going to go
into Averell Harriman's office

00:23:10.340 --> 00:23:13.630
and, hey, I got to change the
batteries on the bug, right?

00:23:13.630 --> 00:23:16.370
So it has to be
completely passive.

00:23:16.370 --> 00:23:20.570
So again, there was this
capacitive inductive circuit

00:23:20.570 --> 00:23:22.340
that had a natural frequency.

00:23:22.340 --> 00:23:24.800
And that natural frequency
would change a little bit

00:23:24.800 --> 00:23:27.290
as you vibrated it.

00:23:27.290 --> 00:23:31.120
And this is very much
like the RFID chip.

00:23:31.120 --> 00:23:33.570
So for example, in the
transponders in your car

00:23:33.570 --> 00:23:35.600
when you go past a
toll plaza, and they

00:23:35.600 --> 00:23:38.030
want to know exactly
where your car is,

00:23:38.030 --> 00:23:39.350
there are multiple frequencies.

00:23:39.350 --> 00:23:43.250
So what happens is that
they beam a radio frequency

00:23:43.250 --> 00:23:46.130
signal at your car-- always
beaming there-- but then,

00:23:46.130 --> 00:23:48.650
it comes back with a
variety of frequencies

00:23:48.650 --> 00:23:50.810
that you can then
look at and uniquely

00:23:50.810 --> 00:23:53.030
identify that that's your car.

00:23:53.030 --> 00:23:55.160
Marathon runners put these
chips in their shoes,

00:23:55.160 --> 00:23:58.900
and you track how they're
going and that sort of thing.

00:23:58.900 --> 00:24:00.590
So here, you have
this thing that's

00:24:00.590 --> 00:24:03.830
oscillating at a
certain frequency that

00:24:03.830 --> 00:24:09.410
is dependent on the capacitance
of that little thing,

00:24:09.410 --> 00:24:11.090
the capacitance changing.

00:24:11.090 --> 00:24:13.220
And so what the
Soviets then did was

00:24:13.220 --> 00:24:16.520
they beamed a radio
frequency signal

00:24:16.520 --> 00:24:18.860
towards Harriman's office.

00:24:18.860 --> 00:24:23.300
And then, that would create some
interference between the two,

00:24:23.300 --> 00:24:26.900
and then it would
naturally rebroadcast out

00:24:26.900 --> 00:24:30.800
the signal, which you could then
use to interrogate and find out

00:24:30.800 --> 00:24:33.290
what people were saying,
much the same way you

00:24:33.290 --> 00:24:36.500
are broadcasting a
signal into the radio

00:24:36.500 --> 00:24:38.810
transponder in
your car, and then

00:24:38.810 --> 00:24:41.910
you're able to get a unique
signature that's coming back.

00:24:41.910 --> 00:24:43.520
So that was the basis of this.

00:24:43.520 --> 00:24:45.470
And the way it was
found, of course,

00:24:45.470 --> 00:24:49.220
is that, ultimately, this
thing has to rebroadcast out

00:24:49.220 --> 00:24:53.090
some sort of signal, the same
way your car's RFID chip would

00:24:53.090 --> 00:24:54.690
broadcast out a signal.

00:24:54.690 --> 00:24:56.990
And so, ultimately,
people were able to detect

00:24:56.990 --> 00:24:59.660
that this radio frequency signal
was getting broadcasted out.

00:24:59.660 --> 00:25:01.659
And they knocked that out.

00:25:01.659 --> 00:25:03.950
And then people started to
look for this sort of thing.

00:25:03.950 --> 00:25:06.140
But then, spy versus
spy-- you always

00:25:06.140 --> 00:25:07.810
have to come up
with a better idea.

00:25:07.810 --> 00:25:10.370
So there was another idea
that the Soviets came up with,

00:25:10.370 --> 00:25:13.106
which was to beam a microwave
signal towards the windows,

00:25:13.106 --> 00:25:14.980
and the windows would
vibrate back and forth,

00:25:14.980 --> 00:25:18.250
and you could listen in doing
that, and on and on and on.

00:25:18.250 --> 00:25:22.450
So I could talk about
electronic espionage forever.

00:25:22.450 --> 00:25:24.280
But I'm not going to.

00:25:24.280 --> 00:25:25.640
And I'll turn it back to Dorit.

00:25:25.640 --> 00:25:27.931
But if people have questions
in the question and answer

00:25:27.931 --> 00:25:30.956
session, we can address it then.

00:25:30.956 --> 00:25:34.780
[APPLAUSE]

00:25:40.050 --> 00:25:42.860
- Yeah, so maybe we have
a little bit more time

00:25:42.860 --> 00:25:47.240
to just see what
happened to the theremin

00:25:47.240 --> 00:25:51.620
after Lev left the
States and disappeared,

00:25:51.620 --> 00:25:55.400
working on other
important devices.

00:25:55.400 --> 00:26:01.850
In the '30s, composers started
to write for the instrument,

00:26:01.850 --> 00:26:05.810
maybe most noted
Messiaen or Percy

00:26:05.810 --> 00:26:09.860
Grainger, Robert Schillinger.

00:26:09.860 --> 00:26:14.080
And Clara Rockmore did
a very good presentation

00:26:14.080 --> 00:26:18.040
as a virtuoso interpreting
the instrument.

00:26:18.040 --> 00:26:21.320
Then, in the late '40s,
the theremin, I guess,

00:26:21.320 --> 00:26:28.010
reached its most defining,
notorious popularity--

00:26:28.010 --> 00:26:29.990
up to now, hopefully--

00:26:29.990 --> 00:26:31.990
through Hollywood.

00:26:31.990 --> 00:26:34.490
That's a sound you
probably heard but didn't

00:26:34.490 --> 00:26:37.250
realize it was a theremin.

00:26:37.250 --> 00:26:43.070
It was first, I think,
started in 1947, Spellbound--

00:26:43.070 --> 00:26:47.360
Miklós Rózsa wrote
a beautiful score--

00:26:47.360 --> 00:26:48.890
the Hitchcock movie.

00:26:48.890 --> 00:26:51.200
And whenever Gregory
Peck would have

00:26:51.200 --> 00:26:57.140
his memory spells,
the sound of madness,

00:26:57.140 --> 00:26:59.600
the theremin lent itself.

00:26:59.600 --> 00:27:03.560
The eerie, almost
like a voice quality,

00:27:03.560 --> 00:27:05.540
was applied there
very effectively.

00:27:05.540 --> 00:27:06.890
And then, it went on from there.

00:27:06.890 --> 00:27:11.390
It turned into the
dramatic voice of madness

00:27:11.390 --> 00:27:12.910
in The Lost Weekend.

00:27:12.910 --> 00:27:16.730
And then, it was discovered
by science fiction and horror

00:27:16.730 --> 00:27:18.870
and represented there.

00:27:18.870 --> 00:27:22.230
And I would like to maybe
play a piece from that era

00:27:22.230 --> 00:27:26.420
by one of my favorite
composers, Bernard Herrmann.

00:27:26.420 --> 00:27:30.590
He did the score for The
Day the Earth Stood Still.

00:27:30.590 --> 00:27:33.710
And you might have
heard that one before.

