Yeah.

00:29:52.610 --> 00:29:54.710
So, yeah.

00:29:54.710 --> 00:29:59.020
This is what the theremin is the
most well-known for, I guess.

00:29:59.020 --> 00:30:02.910
But fact is it can do
much more than that.

00:30:02.910 --> 00:30:09.160
It was then employed by
bands in the '60s and '70s,

00:30:09.160 --> 00:30:14.020
most namely the Beach
Boys or Captain Beefheart,

00:30:14.020 --> 00:30:16.180
or even Led Zeppelin.

00:30:16.180 --> 00:30:20.590
Two days ago, we met Micky
Dolenz of the Monkees.

00:30:20.590 --> 00:30:23.930
And my first question to him
was, have you ever played--

00:30:23.930 --> 00:30:25.240
do you know the theremin?

00:30:25.240 --> 00:30:26.550
And he said, yeah.

00:30:26.550 --> 00:30:32.200
I was at the Beach Boys' studio
and played the theremin there.

00:30:32.200 --> 00:30:37.150
And so obviously, it
was around at that time.

00:30:37.150 --> 00:30:40.090
It's also very interesting
that the theremin is really

00:30:40.090 --> 00:30:44.520
often referred to as the
dinosaurs of the synthesizers.

00:30:44.520 --> 00:30:49.300
Don Buchla and Bob Moog, who
both were the first people

00:30:49.300 --> 00:30:51.370
working and creating
synthesizers,

00:30:51.370 --> 00:30:56.980
they always referenced Lev
Theremin and his device.

00:30:56.980 --> 00:31:03.370
Don Buchla is quoted as saying
Lev was his big idol because he

00:31:03.370 --> 00:31:09.940
is so impressed how he created
the theremin without having

00:31:09.940 --> 00:31:14.080
an oscilloscope and
just a few waves.

00:31:14.080 --> 00:31:17.590
And Bob Moog started
his first company

00:31:17.590 --> 00:31:21.940
when he was 14 building
theremins out of Brooklyn.

00:31:21.940 --> 00:31:24.970
And he is still one of
the main producers--

00:31:24.970 --> 00:31:27.220
his company-- of theremins.

00:31:27.220 --> 00:31:32.440
This is actually a theremini,
kind of a little detour

00:31:32.440 --> 00:31:34.270
of the original theremin.

00:31:34.270 --> 00:31:37.060
But it's light and
portable, so I like it.

00:31:37.060 --> 00:31:40.720
And it's a customized
prototype here.

00:31:40.720 --> 00:31:45.040
But this instrument actually
combines the analog interface

00:31:45.040 --> 00:31:48.130
of the theremin with
digital technology

00:31:48.130 --> 00:31:50.980
by having all these
presets inside.

00:31:50.980 --> 00:31:55.780
And it even has a theremin's
worst enemy, pitch control.

00:31:55.780 --> 00:31:58.990
So why all this effort if
the pitch is controlled?

00:31:58.990 --> 00:32:03.430
But everything you hear from
me is turning all these helpers

00:32:03.430 --> 00:32:07.750
off, and I'm only playing
with the very pure [INAUDIBLE]

00:32:07.750 --> 00:32:12.940
and setting as it
originally was intended.

