for musicians and
composers to dive into that

00:38:00.860 --> 00:38:04.430
and establish and
find that and also

00:38:04.430 --> 00:38:06.890
be able to write that down.

00:38:06.890 --> 00:38:11.160
- So what happens in a typical
theremin society in New York,

00:38:11.160 --> 00:38:14.750
and how do the neighbors
react to the noise?

00:38:14.750 --> 00:38:17.540
- No neighbor is happy when
someone starts taking up

00:38:17.540 --> 00:38:19.385
the theremin, including mine.

00:38:22.880 --> 00:38:26.030
But it is doable.

00:38:26.030 --> 00:38:29.090
And I encourage--
musicians and non-musicians

00:38:29.090 --> 00:38:33.060
have almost an equal
take because it's

00:38:33.060 --> 00:38:36.920
such a different way of
rhetorically approaching it,

00:38:36.920 --> 00:38:38.250
like any other instrument.

00:38:38.250 --> 00:38:41.540
So I think it's a fair game.

00:38:41.540 --> 00:38:43.280
The New York Theremin
Society was really

00:38:43.280 --> 00:38:46.250
founded as a community platform.

00:38:46.250 --> 00:38:51.020
And it turns out there's a
big international community.

00:38:51.020 --> 00:38:58.300
And it really tries to promote
the theremin being applied

00:38:58.300 --> 00:39:01.830
in different forms of arts.

00:39:01.830 --> 00:39:05.660
To give it a proper context,
one of the downfalls, one

00:39:05.660 --> 00:39:08.450
of the curses, of the
theremin is that I don't think

00:39:08.450 --> 00:39:11.270
there are many other instruments
that so easily can sound

00:39:11.270 --> 00:39:14.120
so terrible and unmusical--

00:39:14.120 --> 00:39:15.650
like any other instrument.

00:39:15.650 --> 00:39:18.590
And so a lot of people
might know the theremin

00:39:18.590 --> 00:39:21.860
but permanently
underestimate it and think

00:39:21.860 --> 00:39:25.280
it's only capable to kind of--

00:39:25.280 --> 00:39:27.640
so it really, the New
York Theremin Society

00:39:27.640 --> 00:39:30.380
is one of many
organizations that

00:39:30.380 --> 00:39:35.840
try to guard the context
so people really understand

00:39:35.840 --> 00:39:37.160
what the instrument can do.

00:39:37.160 --> 00:39:39.850
Because it still needs to
be explained, unfortunately.

00:39:39.850 --> 00:39:41.910
Thank you.

00:39:41.910 --> 00:39:44.790
- I have a question for you
about your playing technique.

00:39:44.790 --> 00:39:48.450
I tried a theremin
for all of one day

00:39:48.450 --> 00:39:52.080
and stopped because of
complaints from my neighbors.

00:39:52.080 --> 00:39:54.780
But like most people
who try a theremin,

00:39:54.780 --> 00:39:57.060
usually download a
book by Clara Rockmore

00:39:57.060 --> 00:39:58.860
and look at hand positions.

00:39:58.860 --> 00:40:01.940
And your technique was
totally different from hers.

00:40:01.940 --> 00:40:06.060
And I'm wondering whether you
created your own technique,

00:40:06.060 --> 00:40:10.156
whether all good thereminists
develop their own technique,

00:40:10.156 --> 00:40:12.030
or whether they all
start with Clara Rockmore

00:40:12.030 --> 00:40:13.470
and then move out from there.

00:40:13.470 --> 00:40:14.616
- That's a great question.

00:40:14.616 --> 00:40:15.990
I think the theremin
right now is

00:40:15.990 --> 00:40:20.210
in the stage where the violin
was in the 18th century, where

00:40:20.210 --> 00:40:22.860
different schools
started to sprout

00:40:22.860 --> 00:40:24.690
in different regions
of the world.

00:40:24.690 --> 00:40:28.980
And you actually recognize from
which region the students--

00:40:28.980 --> 00:40:29.910
from which teacher--

00:40:29.910 --> 00:40:31.350
the students come.

00:40:31.350 --> 00:40:34.410
So there are some
players that developed

00:40:34.410 --> 00:40:37.170
very specific techniques.

00:40:37.170 --> 00:40:39.450
And I have no technique.

00:40:39.450 --> 00:40:41.580
And I'm teaching a lot.

00:40:41.580 --> 00:40:47.810
So these techniques
of Clara Rockmore--

00:40:47.810 --> 00:40:51.250
my take is it really depends
on what you want to do,

00:40:51.250 --> 00:40:54.000
what your goal is of
what you want to achieve.

00:40:54.000 --> 00:40:59.310
If you want to play
Rachmaninoff or if you want to--

00:40:59.310 --> 00:41:01.060
so it depends on that.

00:41:01.060 --> 00:41:06.300
And I believe everyone has a
natural, stable hand position.

00:41:06.300 --> 00:41:10.410
And this instrument really
does give the opportunity

00:41:10.410 --> 00:41:12.720
to develop your own
style and get as

00:41:12.720 --> 00:41:15.760
far as you want to get with it.

00:41:15.760 --> 00:41:18.660
And if you choose to find
one of the techniques--

00:41:18.660 --> 00:41:21.060
which now can be found online--

00:41:21.060 --> 00:41:23.490
that might be right for
you, that's OK, too.

00:41:23.490 --> 00:41:25.830
So that kind of freedom
really appealed to me

00:41:25.830 --> 00:41:27.330
when I started
playing the theremin,

00:41:27.330 --> 00:41:31.250
and it might appeal
to others, too.

00:41:31.250 --> 00:41:33.644
- I was wondering,
you mentioned bands

00:41:33.644 --> 00:41:35.810
like the Beach Boys, and
the Rolling Stones, and Led

00:41:35.810 --> 00:41:37.520
Zeppelin, actually, as well.

00:41:37.520 --> 00:41:40.190
And I was wondering in
which tracks, notably,

00:41:40.190 --> 00:41:41.479
is the theremin used?

00:41:41.479 --> 00:41:43.270
Because I've listened
to these bands a lot.

00:41:43.270 --> 00:41:46.070
And they all experiment with
sound and do some weird sounds,

00:41:46.070 --> 00:41:48.990
but I can never tell if it's
guitar or something different.

00:41:48.990 --> 00:41:52.899
So in which tracks is that
the prominent feature?

00:41:52.899 --> 00:41:53.940
- That's a good question.

00:41:53.940 --> 00:41:55.740
Maybe, John, can you
help me with that?

00:41:55.740 --> 00:41:56.740
Do you know?

00:41:56.740 --> 00:41:58.740
- Well, Led Zeppelin,
"Whole Lotta Love."

00:41:58.740 --> 00:42:00.740
That's the most notable one.

00:42:00.740 --> 00:42:04.468
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:42:04.468 --> 00:42:06.798
- Jimmy Page played a
pitch-only theremin.

00:42:06.798 --> 00:42:11.120
- We have a Boston
theremin colleague.

00:42:11.120 --> 00:42:13.120
- Jimmy Page played a
pitch-only theremin.

00:42:13.120 --> 00:42:15.210
It was just one single antenna.

00:42:15.210 --> 00:42:19.520
By pitch-only, I mean there
was no volume control.

00:42:19.520 --> 00:42:24.260
Beach Boys, most notably,
didn't really use a theremin.

00:42:24.260 --> 00:42:26.810
Brian Wilson wanted
that theremin sound.

00:42:26.810 --> 00:42:28.340
He didn't care how he got it.

00:42:28.340 --> 00:42:32.150
So if you've seen the
theremin documentary, which

00:42:32.150 --> 00:42:34.577
Dorit alluded to it--

00:42:34.577 --> 00:42:36.410
there's a theremin
documentary that came out

00:42:36.410 --> 00:42:40.100
about 20 years ago, I guess--

00:42:40.100 --> 00:42:42.050
and they interview
Brian Wilson, and he

00:42:42.050 --> 00:42:43.460
talks about getting a theremin.

00:42:43.460 --> 00:42:46.180
But really, he just
wanted that sound.

00:42:46.180 --> 00:42:49.350
He hired somebody who
said, this is too hard

00:42:49.350 --> 00:42:50.350
to play on the theremin.

00:42:50.350 --> 00:42:54.148
And the guy invented his own
mechanically controlled--

00:42:54.148 --> 00:42:55.341
- [INAUDIBLE]

00:42:55.341 --> 00:42:55.840
- Yeah.

00:42:55.840 --> 00:42:57.239
And then-- yeah.

00:42:57.239 --> 00:42:59.530
It was later dubbed the
Tannerin because the man's name

00:42:59.530 --> 00:43:01.860
was Paul Tanner.

00:43:01.860 --> 00:43:05.920
And then, on tour, even,
the Beach Boys most recently

00:43:05.920 --> 00:43:08.830
used a ribbon-controlled
instrument, as opposed

00:43:08.830 --> 00:43:12.260
to a theremin, just because
it's easier to hit those notes.

00:43:12.260 --> 00:43:15.280
But that sound was used on
songs like "Good Vibrations"

00:43:15.280 --> 00:43:15.910
for that.

00:43:15.910 --> 00:43:19.810
[HUMMING]-- that thing.

00:43:19.810 --> 00:43:23.170
So that's Led Zeppelin
and the Beach Boys.

00:43:23.170 --> 00:43:24.640
But there have been--

00:43:24.640 --> 00:43:28.278
lots of bands today are
using the theremin, as well.

00:43:28.278 --> 00:43:32.710
- It's kind of hard to tell
these days because most likely,

00:43:32.710 --> 00:43:33.940
they're just like Portishead.

00:43:33.940 --> 00:43:38.560
They use a mock synthesizer
to simulate the theremin.

00:43:38.560 --> 00:43:41.440
- The theremin always
has some imperfections.

00:43:41.440 --> 00:43:43.641
If it sounds too good,
it's [INAUDIBLE]..

00:43:43.641 --> 00:43:44.140
- Yeah.

00:43:44.140 --> 00:43:44.639
You know.

00:43:50.540 --> 00:43:52.550
- Actually, I have two parts.

00:43:52.550 --> 00:43:57.190
Have you ever had a chance
to play one of the older

00:43:57.190 --> 00:43:59.650
original instruments?

00:43:59.650 --> 00:44:03.550
And you have a little one.

00:44:03.550 --> 00:44:05.170
Have they sampled that?

00:44:05.170 --> 00:44:06.820
- This is a great question.

00:44:06.820 --> 00:44:09.370
In fact, this is
really interesting

00:44:09.370 --> 00:44:13.240
to know for everyone
that likes the theremin.

00:44:13.240 --> 00:44:15.190
There are a few of
them floating around,

00:44:15.190 --> 00:44:18.850
and there's a
collector in Paris.

00:44:18.850 --> 00:44:21.160
And he had an original.

00:44:21.160 --> 00:44:22.870
He has all functioning
instruments,

00:44:22.870 --> 00:44:27.160
and he had an RCA from
the '20s with the speaker,

00:44:27.160 --> 00:44:32.290
and also the Vanguard--
several different theremins

00:44:32.290 --> 00:44:34.900
from the '50s that
Bob Moog built.

00:44:34.900 --> 00:44:38.925
And trying them out literally
changed my life because--

00:44:38.925 --> 00:44:42.070
and it's something I would
like to organize for next year,

00:44:42.070 --> 00:44:44.060
for the 100th birthday--

00:44:44.060 --> 00:44:48.130
these instruments
make you realize

00:44:48.130 --> 00:44:52.120
why there was such excitement
and such promise back then.

00:44:52.120 --> 00:44:55.360
Because if you listen to all
the theremin we have now,

00:44:55.360 --> 00:44:57.130
they sound like Mickey Mouse.

00:44:57.130 --> 00:45:00.730
They sound like tricycles in
comparison with these theremin.

00:45:00.730 --> 00:45:02.230
They are like big trucks.

00:45:02.230 --> 00:45:04.740
The valves-- they
sound humongous.

00:45:04.740 --> 00:45:07.390
They have a fleshy, big sound.

00:45:07.390 --> 00:45:10.090
It has, also, a lot to
do with the speakers.

00:45:10.090 --> 00:45:12.670
Because fact is,
something that no active

00:45:12.670 --> 00:45:15.740
thereminist these days
takes much in consideration,

00:45:15.740 --> 00:45:16.570
including myself--

00:45:16.570 --> 00:45:18.645
I want to change this ASAP--

00:45:18.645 --> 00:45:20.020
is that, actually,
the instrument

00:45:20.020 --> 00:45:23.800
consists of the theremin
and its speaker.

00:45:23.800 --> 00:45:26.950
And Lev, specifically, also
had the matching speakers.

00:45:26.950 --> 00:45:28.610
So that makes all
the difference.

00:45:28.610 --> 00:45:31.930
So this is also yet one of
the missing links we still

00:45:31.930 --> 00:45:33.400
have to put together.

00:45:33.400 --> 00:45:34.240
Great question.

00:45:34.240 --> 00:45:36.740
Thank you.

00:45:36.740 --> 00:45:37.310
- Hi.

00:45:37.310 --> 00:45:39.140
I was wondering if
I or anyone else

00:45:39.140 --> 00:45:42.350
here was inspired to start
learning the theremin,

00:45:42.350 --> 00:45:45.080
if you would have advice about
where to start or how to start?

00:45:48.140 --> 00:45:50.180
- Yes.

00:45:50.180 --> 00:45:53.390
Pick a song you really
like, and close your eyes,

00:45:53.390 --> 00:45:55.400
and play along to it.

00:45:55.400 --> 00:45:59.120
First lesson, learn how the
volume works to not shoot

00:45:59.120 --> 00:46:02.090
your frequency range.

00:46:02.090 --> 00:46:05.840
And go online and find
out some information.

00:46:05.840 --> 00:46:09.980
But we're trying more and more
to offer theremin lectures

00:46:09.980 --> 00:46:11.320
and theremin classes.

00:46:11.320 --> 00:46:13.400
Because all you really
need is to understand

00:46:13.400 --> 00:46:15.860
how to calibrate
a theremin, which

00:46:15.860 --> 00:46:19.060
means to set the size of the
pitch and the volume antenna

00:46:19.060 --> 00:46:21.740
and how to position yourself
in the most stable position.

00:46:21.740 --> 00:46:23.660
And then, you can
really kind of--

00:46:23.660 --> 00:46:26.390
if you master one
note perfectly,

00:46:26.390 --> 00:46:28.010
you can play the theremin.

00:46:28.010 --> 00:46:29.510
And that's a huge challenge.

00:46:29.510 --> 00:46:30.820
That might take you a year.

00:46:30.820 --> 00:46:33.500
But you're welcome to write.

00:46:33.500 --> 00:46:36.400
We're always happy to
give any kind of advice.

00:46:36.400 --> 00:46:37.720
But yeah.

00:46:37.720 --> 00:46:40.802
I hope this helps.

00:46:40.802 --> 00:46:42.510
- Thank you for a
wonderful presentation.

00:46:42.510 --> 00:46:45.030
At the beginning of your
performance of "The Day

00:46:45.030 --> 00:46:47.310
the Earth Stood Still,"
there was a section

00:46:47.310 --> 00:46:49.110
where the sound quality
went from sounding

00:46:49.110 --> 00:46:52.530
like what a theremin usually
sounds like to this almost

00:46:52.530 --> 00:46:54.290
sound cloud.

00:46:54.290 --> 00:46:55.290
What was going on there?

00:46:55.290 --> 00:46:56.370
Were you using a pedal?

00:46:56.370 --> 00:46:56.875
- Yes.

00:46:56.875 --> 00:46:57.750
- Tell me about that.

00:46:57.750 --> 00:46:58.249
- Yes.

00:46:58.249 --> 00:46:59.040
Very good ears.

00:46:59.040 --> 00:47:03.450
I was, because the sound system
here didn't allow me to add

00:47:03.450 --> 00:47:08.520
a tiny subtle reverb to kind of
widen and fatten the frequency

00:47:08.520 --> 00:47:12.240
like I usually do a little
bit-- we have a very barebone

00:47:12.240 --> 00:47:13.680
technical--

00:47:13.680 --> 00:47:16.230
but it does the job beautifully.

00:47:16.230 --> 00:47:18.690
So that's why I thought
maybe this piece would

00:47:18.690 --> 00:47:20.280
be better if I just have--

00:47:20.280 --> 00:47:23.520
I was looping it
very quickly and then

00:47:23.520 --> 00:47:26.860
realized it's too much, and I
chose to have it clean again.

00:47:26.860 --> 00:47:29.310
So I was just experimenting
in the moment of the song.

00:47:29.310 --> 00:47:31.050
- There's looping and reverb?

00:47:31.050 --> 00:47:31.910
- Yes.

00:47:31.910 --> 00:47:35.321
I was creating a very muddy
reverb by a very fast loop.

00:47:35.321 --> 00:47:35.820
- I see.

00:47:35.820 --> 00:47:36.510
I see.

00:47:36.510 --> 00:47:37.427
That was wonderful.

00:47:37.427 --> 00:47:39.510
Was that part of the
original-- when you performed

00:47:39.510 --> 00:47:41.700
that, was that also how it
was performed for the movie,

00:47:41.700 --> 00:47:42.790
or was that something
you introduced?

00:47:42.790 --> 00:47:43.260
- No.

00:47:43.260 --> 00:47:43.759
No, no, no.

00:47:43.759 --> 00:47:45.650
Back then, they really--

00:47:45.650 --> 00:47:46.860
that's the interesting thing.

00:47:46.860 --> 00:47:49.590
Like a completely
new instrument that's

00:47:49.590 --> 00:47:54.050
invented with such dramatic
new tonal possibilities,

00:47:54.050 --> 00:47:57.270
and the phenomena of
people not having the--

00:47:57.270 --> 00:48:00.930
I'm not ready to really apply
all these new possibilities.

00:48:00.930 --> 00:48:03.270
And Lev wanted his
instrument to be

00:48:03.270 --> 00:48:07.230
taken serious, understandably,
so he applied it to the most

00:48:07.230 --> 00:48:10.260
established music style.

00:48:10.260 --> 00:48:14.080
And that limited
it a little bit.

00:48:14.080 --> 00:48:16.175
And so that's why it
kind of got stuck.

00:48:16.175 --> 00:48:16.675
- Yeah.

00:48:16.675 --> 00:48:17.841
Well, that was a revelation.

00:48:17.841 --> 00:48:20.400
It was like all the other
theremin music I've heard

00:48:20.400 --> 00:48:25.590
is like watching a Lamborghini
go up and down a neighborhood

00:48:25.590 --> 00:48:26.432
street.

00:48:26.432 --> 00:48:28.890
And when you did that, it just
opened it up and took it out

00:48:28.890 --> 00:48:29.680
onto the open road.

00:48:29.680 --> 00:48:30.060
So that was really interesting.

00:48:30.060 --> 00:48:30.870
Thank you.

00:48:30.870 --> 00:48:31.380
- Thank you.

00:48:31.380 --> 00:48:32.750
I'm glad.

00:48:32.750 --> 00:48:34.400
Yeah.

00:48:34.400 --> 00:48:36.470
- So obviously, you need
to have a lot of control

00:48:36.470 --> 00:48:37.790
to play the theremin.

00:48:37.790 --> 00:48:40.820
Is it possible to play it
with your head or your arm?

00:48:40.820 --> 00:48:42.830
- Yes.

00:48:42.830 --> 00:48:44.750
So when I started
to teach children--

00:48:44.750 --> 00:48:46.430
because I believe
there's not really

00:48:46.430 --> 00:48:50.450
much electronic early
music education around,

00:48:50.450 --> 00:48:54.200
and children being familiar
with the iPad and all

00:48:54.200 --> 00:48:57.860
these interactive things, but
actually physically creating

00:48:57.860 --> 00:48:59.390
the sound to motion
and motoric--

00:48:59.390 --> 00:49:01.010
it makes so much sense.

00:49:01.010 --> 00:49:03.020
And the really little
ones, from four-year-olds,

00:49:03.020 --> 00:49:05.750
they bring their favorite
teddy bears, and I ask them,

00:49:05.750 --> 00:49:06.950
can you play it with--

00:49:06.950 --> 00:49:10.610
so you can play it with
your nose, with your butt--

00:49:10.610 --> 00:49:16.010
whichever object, whichever
part of your body is the closest

00:49:16.010 --> 00:49:18.150
and shortens the
frequencies-- so it could be--

00:49:20.910 --> 00:49:23.778
so infinite possibilities.

00:49:23.778 --> 00:49:24.278
- Hello.

00:49:24.278 --> 00:49:24.778
- Hello.

