00:50:18.990 --> 00:50:19.940
Maybe--

00:50:19.940 --> 00:50:20.550
- Oh, no.

00:50:20.550 --> 00:50:22.890
I think-- I'm sure
this can be done.

00:50:22.890 --> 00:50:26.760
But the question is if you would
be interested in doing that.

00:50:26.760 --> 00:50:29.360
Because you would
be limiting yourself

00:50:29.360 --> 00:50:32.976
to just playing specific
notes that you allow yourself.

00:50:32.976 --> 00:50:34.350
Because anything
you play will be

00:50:34.350 --> 00:50:36.350
matching this part of the song.

00:50:36.350 --> 00:50:38.765
But it would make it much
easier for any novice to play.

00:50:38.765 --> 00:50:40.890
- Well, it's really
interesting what you're saying.

00:50:40.890 --> 00:50:43.540
You should go and work for
Moog Music immediately.

00:50:43.540 --> 00:50:44.250
They want you.

00:50:44.250 --> 00:50:46.630
Because that's what
this instrument--

00:50:46.630 --> 00:50:49.200
that's actually a new
invention that this instrument

00:50:49.200 --> 00:50:50.280
brought to the market.

00:50:50.280 --> 00:50:55.260
And these thereminis,
they do exactly that.

00:50:55.260 --> 00:50:58.620
You can set the range,
and you can set the key.

00:50:58.620 --> 00:51:00.660
And when you turn
the pitch control on,

00:51:00.660 --> 00:51:02.620
you play along to a song.

00:51:02.620 --> 00:51:06.750
So I can have 10 four-year-olds
in a circle playing

00:51:06.750 --> 00:51:07.400
10 theremins.

00:51:07.400 --> 00:51:09.930
They're all on the same setting,
and they play Kraftwerk,

00:51:09.930 --> 00:51:12.600
and it sounds perfectly in key.

00:51:12.600 --> 00:51:13.710
It's a miracle.

00:51:13.710 --> 00:51:15.690
Because the wrong
notes are filtered out.

00:51:15.690 --> 00:51:17.610
It's exactly what
you're describing.

00:51:17.610 --> 00:51:18.540
That was their idea.

00:51:18.540 --> 00:51:20.190
They came up with
that two years ago.

00:51:20.190 --> 00:51:23.910
And a lot of thereminists
were really angry

00:51:23.910 --> 00:51:26.830
when this came on the market.

00:51:26.830 --> 00:51:29.130
And also, when
things are not fully

00:51:29.130 --> 00:51:32.280
established yet, a lot of
people kind of hoarding it

00:51:32.280 --> 00:51:35.640
and want it all to
themselves, like I'm the--

00:51:35.640 --> 00:51:40.470
and I really believe that we
need inclusivity and community.

00:51:40.470 --> 00:51:43.630
And the more people, the more
it can grow into a movement.

00:51:43.630 --> 00:51:45.810
And so this instrument
really makes

00:51:45.810 --> 00:51:49.570
that bridge of having
an easy result.

00:51:49.570 --> 00:51:52.480
Because it is really,
really hard to play.

00:51:52.480 --> 00:51:53.730
So it sounds good.

00:51:53.730 --> 00:51:56.670
You have the filter, the
few notes that fit, exactly,

00:51:56.670 --> 00:51:57.990
a scale.

00:51:57.990 --> 00:51:59.470
And then, if you
really go further,

00:51:59.470 --> 00:52:02.220
you can turn it
off and go on so.

00:52:02.220 --> 00:52:02.760
Yeah.

00:52:02.760 --> 00:52:03.307
Amazing.

00:52:03.307 --> 00:52:04.890
That's exactly what
they came up with.

00:52:04.890 --> 00:52:05.848
- So you approve of it?

00:52:05.848 --> 00:52:07.000
You approve of this?

00:52:07.000 --> 00:52:08.230
- Yes.

00:52:08.230 --> 00:52:09.810
I approve of it for teaching.

00:52:09.810 --> 00:52:11.291
And yes.

00:52:11.291 --> 00:52:13.290
That's really what the
Moog people came up with,

00:52:13.290 --> 00:52:14.820
and you just had the same idea.

00:52:14.820 --> 00:52:15.000
- OK.

00:52:15.000 --> 00:52:15.090
Thanks.

00:52:15.090 --> 00:52:15.630
- Excellent.

00:52:15.630 --> 00:52:18.190
Wow.

00:52:18.190 --> 00:52:19.180
- Thank you very much.

00:52:19.180 --> 00:52:21.910
I actually have a question
for your science colleague,

00:52:21.910 --> 00:52:22.881
if that's all right.

00:52:22.881 --> 00:52:23.380
- OK.

00:52:23.380 --> 00:52:23.920
You're putting me on the spot.

00:52:23.920 --> 00:52:25.910
- And it may seem a
little far afield,

00:52:25.910 --> 00:52:28.510
but listening to
your presentation,

00:52:28.510 --> 00:52:30.280
I've always been a
fan of the theremin,

00:52:30.280 --> 00:52:33.310
especially the years I
was living in Budapest.

00:52:33.310 --> 00:52:36.730
But I'm very interested in what
you said about the early use

00:52:36.730 --> 00:52:38.180
for spycraft.

00:52:38.180 --> 00:52:43.240
And thinking about the recent
microwave problems in Havana,

00:52:43.240 --> 00:52:45.280
could you please
help us understand

00:52:45.280 --> 00:52:46.660
if that's related to this?

00:52:46.660 --> 00:52:48.995
Or is there anything you
can offer to us about that?

00:52:48.995 --> 00:52:51.370
- Well, I don't know much--
let me say one thing I missed

00:52:51.370 --> 00:52:52.750
at the beginning.

00:52:52.750 --> 00:52:55.300
I just wanted to sort of fill
out what I should have said.

00:52:55.300 --> 00:52:58.450
So this alarm that
Dorit mentioned,

00:52:58.450 --> 00:53:01.660
it's a whole class of sensors
called proximity sensors.

00:53:01.660 --> 00:53:04.870
And that was the alarm
that used-- so, in a sense,

00:53:04.870 --> 00:53:07.720
you could never enter a
room without broadcasting

00:53:07.720 --> 00:53:10.570
your presence in an
electromagnetic sense.

00:53:10.570 --> 00:53:13.000
And so the idea of
these alarm systems

00:53:13.000 --> 00:53:16.420
was using the
capacitance of your body

00:53:16.420 --> 00:53:19.200
to basically set off the alarm.

00:53:19.200 --> 00:53:21.550
And so that's what got
him thinking about how

00:53:21.550 --> 00:53:23.530
to do this as a theremin.

00:53:23.530 --> 00:53:25.330
I don't know exactly--

00:53:25.330 --> 00:53:26.860
we don't know exactly--

00:53:26.860 --> 00:53:29.050
what was going on
with the embassies.

00:53:29.050 --> 00:53:32.410
But we do know that microwaves--

00:53:32.410 --> 00:53:34.960
just look at what happens
in the oven, right?

00:53:34.960 --> 00:53:37.810
You put something in
the oven, and the way

00:53:37.810 --> 00:53:42.310
a microwave oven works is that
there is a certain frequency

00:53:42.310 --> 00:53:44.170
that excites water molecules.

00:53:44.170 --> 00:53:47.290
And it's close to a certain
microwave frequency.

00:53:47.290 --> 00:53:51.280
So if you have a microwave
oscillator called a klystron,

00:53:51.280 --> 00:53:55.060
and it's tuned to the frequency
of this vibrational state

00:53:55.060 --> 00:53:57.790
in water, it'll heat it up.

00:53:57.790 --> 00:54:01.880
And so our bodies are
mostly made out of water.

00:54:01.880 --> 00:54:07.360
So if you focus a microwave
beam at that frequency

00:54:07.360 --> 00:54:10.720
and point it at somebody,
you can basically

00:54:10.720 --> 00:54:13.460
kill them, or give them
a substantial disruption.

00:54:13.460 --> 00:54:17.020
So my guess-- and I don't
know because, clearly, it's

00:54:17.020 --> 00:54:22.060
classified-- is that there was
some sort of focused microwave

00:54:22.060 --> 00:54:23.950
beam that was developed
by the Russians,

00:54:23.950 --> 00:54:27.040
and then they decided to
test drive it in Havana.

00:54:27.040 --> 00:54:28.030
That's my best guess.

00:54:28.030 --> 00:54:30.880
- The reason I raised it--
it seems very far afield--

00:54:30.880 --> 00:54:34.090
is that the first symptoms
were about ringing and hearing

00:54:34.090 --> 00:54:34.720
sounds.

00:54:34.720 --> 00:54:38.015
And I thought maybe
that was related.

00:54:38.015 --> 00:54:38.890
- Well, I don't know.

00:54:38.890 --> 00:54:40.110
It could be.

00:54:40.110 --> 00:54:42.170
Now that you mention
it, I did see that.

00:54:42.170 --> 00:54:46.140
And so I don't know.

00:54:46.140 --> 00:54:48.640
It could have been
some sort of modulation

00:54:48.640 --> 00:54:51.750
that used some sort of a
resonant frequency in the head.

00:54:51.750 --> 00:54:54.600
Like, maybe what you can do
is tune it until you get--

00:54:54.600 --> 00:54:56.210
you know, when we
produce voices,

00:54:56.210 --> 00:54:57.840
we have different vowel sounds.

00:54:57.840 --> 00:54:59.850
And the vowel sounds
get varied because we

00:54:59.850 --> 00:55:01.766
have the pharynx
as one resonance

00:55:01.766 --> 00:55:04.140
and then, depending on where
the tongue is in your mouth,

00:55:04.140 --> 00:55:05.460
we get another resonance.

00:55:05.460 --> 00:55:07.890
And then, the nasal
cavities have yet another.

00:55:07.890 --> 00:55:11.160
So it's conceivable that maybe
what they're trying to do

00:55:11.160 --> 00:55:14.990
is to make the resonances,
our body resonances,

00:55:14.990 --> 00:55:15.940
go nuts or something.

00:55:15.940 --> 00:55:16.270
- OK.

00:55:16.270 --> 00:55:16.400
Thank you.

00:55:16.400 --> 00:55:17.024
- It's a guess.

00:55:19.890 --> 00:55:24.450
- I imagine with AI,
you could probably

00:55:24.450 --> 00:55:28.590
get a lot of different
robots doing these things.

00:55:28.590 --> 00:55:34.890
And wouldn't it be
possible to visualize

00:55:34.890 --> 00:55:37.890
the function of their
systems, the function

00:55:37.890 --> 00:55:44.850
of our different systems, and
the function of the instrument?

00:55:44.850 --> 00:55:49.260
- I'm not sure exactly--
you mean trying to have

00:55:49.260 --> 00:55:52.673
a mathematical model or
a simulation of that?

00:55:52.673 --> 00:55:53.172
- Right.

00:55:53.172 --> 00:55:56.610
Plot the differences
so you can analyze it.

00:55:56.610 --> 00:55:57.764
- Oh, yeah.

00:55:57.764 --> 00:55:58.430
So I don't know.

00:55:58.430 --> 00:56:02.290
Has anybody produced a robot
who can play the theremin?

00:56:02.290 --> 00:56:03.960
- I've been
fantasizing about this

00:56:03.960 --> 00:56:06.660
and started to work
with someone on that.

00:56:06.660 --> 00:56:09.030
But it's a long-term project.

00:56:09.030 --> 00:56:09.530
But yeah.

00:56:09.530 --> 00:56:11.550
It doesn't-- not to my
knowledge that it exists,

00:56:11.550 --> 00:56:14.761
but I think it should exist.

00:56:14.761 --> 00:56:17.260
Because you could play, maybe,
really well because you would

00:56:17.260 --> 00:56:20.060
have really stable movements.

00:56:20.060 --> 00:56:20.624
- Right.

00:56:20.624 --> 00:56:21.540
So what you could do--

00:56:21.540 --> 00:56:24.260
I'm just riffing on this--
but I could imagine.

00:56:24.260 --> 00:56:26.090
- What would you do
with understanding

00:56:26.090 --> 00:56:29.220
the difference and the
functions of the system, anyway?

00:56:29.220 --> 00:56:32.400
- Well, I think that you would
get much more precise control

00:56:32.400 --> 00:56:33.090
over the sounds.

00:56:33.090 --> 00:56:35.100
Because what would
happen would be,

00:56:35.100 --> 00:56:37.470
there's a certain
feedback between--

00:56:37.470 --> 00:56:39.210
I'd have to ask a
performance artist--

00:56:39.210 --> 00:56:43.140
but I would imagine that there's
some feedback between what

00:56:43.140 --> 00:56:45.090
you're hearing and
where the hand is.

00:56:45.090 --> 00:56:47.820
And so if your hand's a
little off in frequency,

00:56:47.820 --> 00:56:50.740
you would alter it until it
hits the right frequencies.

00:56:50.740 --> 00:56:55.100
And I would imagine, perhaps,
with a robot, because their CPU

00:56:55.100 --> 00:56:59.130
cycles are so much faster, that
they could hit more precisely

00:56:59.130 --> 00:57:02.910
and more quickly that note and
might not have to fall back

00:57:02.910 --> 00:57:05.520
on vibrato to tune things.

00:57:05.520 --> 00:57:11.690
- Well, we tested it
with some automated hand,

00:57:11.690 --> 00:57:13.880
like robot machine hands.

00:57:13.880 --> 00:57:15.990
But it became
apparent very quickly

00:57:15.990 --> 00:57:21.090
that that specific model was
moving too coarse and too fast

00:57:21.090 --> 00:57:24.050
and too jagged.

00:57:24.050 --> 00:57:26.040
I'm talking European
measurements now.

00:57:26.040 --> 00:57:29.700
We're talking about
millimeter distances.

00:57:29.700 --> 00:57:32.320
So I'm sure it could be done.

00:57:32.320 --> 00:57:36.120
But when I tried it
out, that robot hand

00:57:36.120 --> 00:57:38.490
couldn't master the theremin.

00:57:38.490 --> 00:57:39.070
- Yeah.

00:57:39.070 --> 00:57:41.960
So that's an interesting
thought for the future.

00:57:41.960 --> 00:57:44.260
- Well, I was just
wondering, through that kind

00:57:44.260 --> 00:57:48.400
of creativity, could you
find any new information

00:57:48.400 --> 00:57:52.030
about creativity or physics?

00:57:52.030 --> 00:57:56.610
- Information about the
creative process, for example?

00:57:56.610 --> 00:57:57.110
Yeah.

00:57:57.110 --> 00:57:57.890
Could be.

00:57:57.890 --> 00:57:59.930
There are some interesting--

00:57:59.930 --> 00:58:02.480
I don't know it in
a musical context,

00:58:02.480 --> 00:58:08.810
but there is a deep learning
project called DeepDream

00:58:08.810 --> 00:58:11.300
that Google has.

00:58:11.300 --> 00:58:18.020
And what it does is it tries
to do pattern recognition

00:58:18.020 --> 00:58:22.130
and then impose or
reimpose on the image

00:58:22.130 --> 00:58:25.910
that it's been given new
images and twist it around.

00:58:25.910 --> 00:58:30.800
So if you actually google the
word DeepDream, what you can do

00:58:30.800 --> 00:58:33.090
is you can take an image,
deposit it, and then

00:58:33.090 --> 00:58:36.500
it'll run its algorithm and
try to do pattern recognition.

00:58:36.500 --> 00:58:39.770
And so if you take something
like a rocky cliff face

00:58:39.770 --> 00:58:43.954
or kind of the jagged
structure of a gnarly tree

00:58:43.954 --> 00:58:46.370
and you put it through there
several times, what'll emerge

00:58:46.370 --> 00:58:49.760
are the faces of birds
or dogs or reptiles.

00:58:49.760 --> 00:58:52.970
Because the training set
that's been used on that

00:58:52.970 --> 00:58:55.820
is sort of keyed in
to dogs and reptiles

00:58:55.820 --> 00:58:57.350
and that sort of thing.

00:58:57.350 --> 00:58:59.840
So you can imagine
that if you trained

00:58:59.840 --> 00:59:03.760
some sort of deep
learning project

00:59:03.760 --> 00:59:06.740
and you've perfected a robot
that actually can do it

00:59:06.740 --> 00:59:09.530
without these problems,
you could imagine

00:59:09.530 --> 00:59:12.740
that it would impose
its own aesthetic

00:59:12.740 --> 00:59:15.440
and make its own
compositions, which

00:59:15.440 --> 00:59:17.540
is sort of what the deep
learning is getting to.

00:59:17.540 --> 00:59:18.581
But it's not quite there.

00:59:18.581 --> 00:59:21.530
So I would say the robotics
is not up to the task yet.

00:59:21.530 --> 00:59:23.910
And the deep learning is
not up to the task yet.

00:59:23.910 --> 00:59:26.570
But you could imagine that,
at some point in the future,

00:59:26.570 --> 00:59:29.630
the combination of
the two could produce

00:59:29.630 --> 00:59:35.180
its own creative, non-human
way of producing music.

00:59:38.734 --> 00:59:39.400
- Last question?

00:59:42.037 --> 00:59:43.620
- Could you tell a
little more about--

00:59:43.620 --> 00:59:46.210
I understand that
he married a dancer

00:59:46.210 --> 00:59:48.520
and then tried to
see if a dancer could

00:59:48.520 --> 00:59:51.490
dance within a field.

00:59:51.490 --> 00:59:52.690
- Oh, yeah.

00:59:52.690 --> 00:59:53.380
Yeah.

00:59:53.380 --> 00:59:57.130
Lev Theremin, while
he was in New York,

00:59:57.130 --> 01:00:00.550
he also worked on
the terpsitone, which

01:00:00.550 --> 01:00:04.060
is a theremin made for dancers.

01:00:04.060 --> 01:00:08.290
And maybe it was inspired by
his wife, Lavinia Williams.

01:00:08.290 --> 01:00:13.810
But it seemed that nobody really
could control the terpsitone.

01:00:13.810 --> 01:00:16.990
Because again, the
body would just

01:00:16.990 --> 01:00:21.910
move too much to really turn
it into a melodic device.

01:00:21.910 --> 01:00:26.110
There is, right now, a
project in Paris premiering

01:00:26.110 --> 01:00:27.400
at the Pompidou.

01:00:27.400 --> 01:00:28.900
And I'm very happy about it.

01:00:28.900 --> 01:00:32.920
It features seven terpsitones
and three dancers.

01:00:32.920 --> 01:00:35.980
And I was helping with
the consultation--

01:00:35.980 --> 01:00:39.790
because they really didn't
understand it's all about

01:00:39.790 --> 01:00:46.480
calibrating the theremin, like
setting the size of the fields

01:00:46.480 --> 01:00:49.750
which you can do of the
pitch of the volume--

01:00:49.750 --> 01:00:54.390
and so help them
to understand which

01:00:54.390 --> 01:00:58.000
distances work for them and
the kind of things they can do.

01:00:58.000 --> 01:01:00.610
So it's ambitiously
being applied again.

01:01:00.610 --> 01:01:04.640
But to turn that musical
is very difficult.

01:01:04.640 --> 01:01:07.960
One of my favorite inventions
that Lev Theremin also did,

01:01:07.960 --> 01:01:09.850
aside from all the
things we mentioned,

01:01:09.850 --> 01:01:13.930
is the rhythmicon, which is
a huge, clunky rhythm machine

01:01:13.930 --> 01:01:17.200
that couldn't hold the beat.

01:01:17.200 --> 01:01:18.220
I think that's very--

01:01:18.220 --> 01:01:20.470
and it sounds like a
Frankenstein device.

01:01:20.470 --> 01:01:22.360
Anyway, any other questions?

01:01:22.360 --> 01:01:23.680
Oh, thank you.

01:01:23.680 --> 01:01:27.010
- Well, I have to
say without hyperbole

01:01:27.010 --> 01:01:28.930
that the theremin is cool.

01:01:28.930 --> 01:01:30.058
That was great.

